did.abstract: The Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering Records document the administration and activities of the department.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection contains some restricted material. Restrictions related to specific material are listed in the detailed contents list. This collection may require review before it is available for use. Please contact DCA for further details.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Transferred by the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, 2018.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is arranged in eight series: Student files; Office files; Course files; Faculty files; Eta Kappa Nu files; Photographs; 2017 accessions; and 2018 accessions. Arrangement within series varies; original order was maintained where discernible.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Department of Electrical Engineering has its origins in a three-year course of study in "Electrical Science" instituted in 1883. Though the program was initially held "as demand warranted it", it became popular enough to formally establish the Department of Electrical Engineering in 1890. After expanding its curriculum to include computer science classes, the department was renamed the Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science in 1994. In 2003, the department became the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, and the Department of Computer Science split off into its own department. The program was originally a three-year program focused in Electrical Science, with a concentration in commercial applications. The resulting degree was a Bachelor of Mechanic Arts, with the designation of "Electrical" to appear on the diploma. However, for the 1892-1893 academic year, the engineering curriculum was increased to a four-year plan of study, with candidates for degrees to be awarded a Bachelor of Electrical Engineering. This increase resulted in a housing crisis that touched on each engineering department; though the Department of Electrical Engineering was originally housed in Ballou Hall, it utilized the newly added Bromfield Pearson School, Robinson Hall, and Howe Laboratory for laboratory and classroom space in subsequent years. The Department of Electrical Engineering had a close connection with the American Radio and Research Corporation (AMRAD) while the company was active on campus. AMRAD had built two buildings in close proximity to Tufts; a small laboratory in 1915 on the north side of campus, and a manufacturing plant in 1920 across the Boston and Maine railroad tracks. The Department of Electrical Engineering used the laboratory facilities for several years to provide training in radio communications. After AMRAD declared bankruptcy in 1925 and sold its buildings to Tufts, the Electrical Engineering Department used the laboratory as its headquarters. In 1931, during the construction of Cousens Gymnasium, the manufacturing plant was renovated to become a wing of the gym. After construction was complete, the Department of Electrical Engineering moved to this wing. This wing was dedicated as Hooper Laboratory in 1940 and was later renovated and renamed Halligan Hall in 1983. As of 2017, it continues to house the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering as well as the Department of Computer Science. From 1890 until his death in 1918, William Hooper served as the department's only full professor. Additional influential figures who served the department were Edwin B. Rollins, full professor and chair of the department from 1928 to 1943, and Melville S. Munro, who acted as a professor of the department from 1913 to 1941. Noticeable increases in enrollment have occurred twice in the department's history. From the early 20th century through the First World War, all departments within the Engineering School faced a rapid increase in interest, resulting in overenrollment. Though 1907 changes in admissions standards somewhat relieved the problem, the school remained over-enrolled until the 1920s, when the curriculum was revised and enrollment waned. During the 1970s and into the late 1980s, enrollment in the Department of Electrical Engineering surged, with the number of students graduating from the department peaking close to 100 in 1987. This increase in enrollment was attributed to increased interest in computers. After 1987, the number of degrees granted by the department steadily decreased until the early 1990's, when the number of degrees granted each year remained steady. The introduction of a Bachelor of Science in Computer Engineering in 1994 has not changed the enrollment of the department in either direction; the combined number of degrees in Electrical Engineering and Computer Engineering remained consistent with the number of degrees previously granted in Electrical Engineering alone.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering Records, 1890-2018. Tufts University. Digital Collections and Archives. Medford, MA.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Processing of 2017 accessions completed by Leah Edelman in 2017, and 2018 accessions by Leah Edelman and Jady Zhang in 2018. Materials were placed in archival boxes if the original housing was damaged; received order was maintained. A box-level inventory and series-level description were created, and the finding aid was updated at the time of processing.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering records document the administration and activities of the department, including administrative files, faculty files, student academic records, and course documentation. Also included are department-related news clippings and newsletters as well as an extensive collection of photographs.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Some material in this collection may be protected by copyright and other rights. Please see "Reproductions and Use" on the Digital Collections and Archives website for more information about reproductions and permission to publish. Copyright to all materials created by Tufts University employees in the course of their work is held by the Trustees of Tufts University.
